{{Infobox military person |name=Andreas Platis |image=Andreas Platis.jpg |caption=Platis as a Major General in 1921 |birth_date=1865 |death_date= |birth_place=[[Athens]] |death_place= |placeofburial= |placeofburial_label= |nickname= |allegiance={{flagicon|Greece|royal}} [[Kingdom of Greece]] |branch=[[Hellenic Army|Army]] |serviceyears=1888&ndash;1917, 1920&ndash;1923 |rank=[[Lieutenant General|Lt. General]] |unit= |commands=[[III Army Corps (Greece)|III Army Corps]] |battles=[[Greco-Turkish War of 1897]], [[Balkan Wars]], [[Asia Minor Campaign]] |awards= |laterwork= }} '''Andreas Platis''' ({{lang-el|Ανδρέας Πλατής}}) was a [[Greece|Greek]] Army officer who reached the rank of Lieutenant General.
== Biography == Born in [[Athens]] on 3 November 1865, he enrolled in the [[Greek Army Academy]] and graduated on 11 August 1888 as an Infantry 2nd Lieutenant. He fought in the [[Greco-Turkish War of 1897]] and was a battalion commander of the 17th Infantry Regiment in the [[Balkan Wars]]. A moderate royalist, he was dismissed from the army by the [[Venizelists]] in 1917–1920, but was recommissioned following the Venzelist [[Greek legislative election, 1920|electoral defeat]] in November 1920. In 1921 he assumed command of the [[7th Infantry Division (Greece)|7th Infantry Division]], which he led in the [[Battle of Afyonkarahisar–Eskişehir|Greek summer offensive]] and the [[Battle of Sakarya|advance]] towards the [[Sakarya River]]. In June 1922 he was named CO of the Smyrna Superior General Military Command, covering the [[Army of Asia Minor]]'s rear areas. Following the [[Battle of Dumlupınar|Turkish offensive]] in August and the collapse of the Greek army, he assumed for a short time command of the Greek troops in the [[Erythrae]]an peninsula, before they were evacuated to Greece. He did not take part in the [[September 1922 Revolution]], and went into retirement along with several other pro-royalist sympathizers in November 1923.
